&gt; &gt; Charlie,
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; I think it is reasonable to ask that a test with an assumption fail 
&gt; &gt; (or at least be marked ignored) if *all* the test data fails the 
&gt; &gt; assumption.  A test that never executes because its assumption is 
&gt; &gt; never satisfied is counterproductive.  In this case, a 
&gt; failure would 
&gt; &gt; alert the user could fix the assumption, update the test data, or 
&gt; &gt; remove the test entirely if it&#39;s no longer needed.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Rocco
&gt; &gt; 
